Java Data Structures
Data structures are techniques for storing and organizing data efficiently. They allow you to manage information in ways that make access, updates, and searches faster and more convenient.
An array is the simplest example: it lets you store multiple elements in a single variable. But Java goes far beyond arrays, offering powerful data structures in the java.util package. Each serves a different purpose depending on how you want to handle data.
Think of data structures as arrays on steroids—more flexible, feature-rich, and tailored for specific needs.

🔹 ArrayList
- A resizable array that grows as needed.
- Stores elements and lets you access them by index.
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    ArrayList<String> cars = new ArrayList<>();
    cars.add("Volvo");
    cars.add("BMW");
    cars.add("Ford");
    cars.add("Mazda");
    System.out.println(cars);
  }
}



🔹 HashSet
- A collection of unique elements—duplicates are not allowed.
- Great for fast membership checks.
import java.util.HashSet;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    HashSet<String> cars = new HashSet<>();
    cars.add("Volvo");
    cars.add("BMW");
    cars.add("Ford");
    cars.add("BMW"); // Duplicate
    cars.add("Mazda");
    System.out.println(cars);
  }
}


👉 Notice that "BMW" only appears once because sets enforce uniqueness.

🔹 HashMap
- Stores key-value pairs.
- Perfect when you want to look up values by a unique key (like an ID or name).
import java.util.HashMap;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    HashMap<String, String> capitalCities = new HashMap<>();
    capitalCities.put("England", "London");
    capitalCities.put("Germany", "Berlin");
    capitalCities.put("Norway", "Oslo");
    capitalCities.put("USA", "Washington DC");
    System.out.println(capitalCities);
  }
}






🔹 Iterators
An iterator is a tool for looping through elements in a data structure. “Iterating” simply means going through items one by one.
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Iterator;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    ArrayList<String> cars = new ArrayList<>();
    cars.add("Volvo");
    cars.add("BMW");
    cars.add("Ford");
    cars.add("Mazda");

    Iterator<String> it = cars.iterator();
    while(it.hasNext()) {
      System.out.println(it.next());
    }
  }
}




Java collections


 Java Collections Framework
Before diving deeper into ArrayList, HashSet, HashMap, and other data structures, it’s important to understand the bigger picture: the Java Collections Framework (JCF).
The JCF provides:
- Interfaces (like List, Set, and Map) that define behavior.
- Classes (like ArrayList, HashSet, HashMap) that implement those interfaces.
All of these are part of the java.util package, offering standardized ways to store, search, sort, and organize data.
👉 Think of the Collections Framework as a toolbox:
- Interfaces are the blueprint of tools.
- Classes are the actual tools you use.

Core Interfaces and Their Implementations
Interface	 	Common Classes				Description
List			ArrayList, LinkedList		Maintains order and allows duplicate elements
Set	HashSet, 	TreeSet, LinkedHashSet		Stores only unique elements
Map	HashMap, 	TreeMap, LinkedHashMap		Stores data as key-value pairs with unique keys



🧩 When to Use What
- List → When order matters, duplicates are allowed, and you need index-based access.
- Set → When you need uniqueness and don’t care about duplicates.
- Map → When you need to store and retrieve values by a key (like a dictionary or phonebook).




